 That's correct! The "break" statement is used to terminate a loop or switch statement early. It can be used to exit a loop or switch statement when a certain condition is met, rather than waiting for the loop to complete its full iteration.

Here's an example of how "break" can be used in a loop:
```
while (true) {
  // do something
  if (someCondition) {
    break;
  }
}
```
In this example, the loop will continue to run indefinitely until the "someCondition" variable is set to true. When that happens, the "break" statement will be executed, and the loop will terminate immediately.

"Break" can also be used in a switch statement to exit the switch block early. For example:
```
switch (someVariable) {
  case 1:
    // do something
    break;
  case 2:
    // do something else
    break;
  default:
    // do something else
    break;
}
```
In this example, the switch statement will execute the code for the first case, and then exit the switch block when the "break" statement is reached.

